Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 57th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
I=E2=80=99m writing this on the return flight back from a 6 hour business t=
rip in Colorado. I left NYC at 5am, spent the day in Denver and will be bac=
k in NYC before midnight. You see, aside from writing this newsletter, I ru=
n a business called Create [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/a4c131d4-ef56=
-4216-822a-40196cfee4ef?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. We sell creatine monohydrate gummies [ https://link.sbst=
ck.com/redirect/a4c131d4-ef56-4216-822a-40196cfee4ef?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ]. Why do I bring this up? Wel=
l, oddly enough, creatine comes up twice in this week=E2=80=99s newsletter.=
 Creatine and optimism. That=E2=80=99s what we do here.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Write of Passage [ https://li=
nk.sbstck.com/redirect/bc3b850f-6feb-41a8-8262-680ec56299f5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy here. Really, every Not Boring is kinda brought to you by Write of Pa=
ssage [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/bc3b850f-6feb-41a8-8262-680ec56299=
f5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
In 2019, as I was thinking about leaving Breather, I decided to start writi=
ng to stretch my brain a little and see if I could shake any magic out of t=
he internet. I saw a tweet from David Perell about a new course he was star=
ting: Write of Passage [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/bc3b850f-6feb-41a=
8-8262-680ec56299f5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Perfect timing.=20
The course changed the trajectory of my life and career. It helped my find =
my Personal Monopoly, start my Substack, and build a habit of writing every=
 week that=E2=80=99s persisted for four years. And Write of Passage has now=
 done the same thing for hundreds of other people. I got to join the last c=
lass of a recent cohort and was blown away by how much the course meant to =
people. WoP just keeps getting better and better.=20
The next cohort of Write of Passage starts later this fall and open-enrollm=
ent starts September 12th. But prior to that, Write of Passage is offering =
a free workshop with Cultural Tudor [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/5afa=
1aaf-7218-4b11-80fa-d44f2a910bb1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. In the workshop, you=E2=80=99ll learn how he we=
nt from working at McDonalds to 1.5M Twitter followers all by writing onlin=
e. Grow Your Audience with the Cultural Tutor [ https://link.sbstck.com/red=
irect/bc3b850f-6feb-41a8-8262-680ec56299f5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in on Wednesday September 6th, but you=
 can register now [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/bc3b850f-6feb-41a8-826=
2-680ec56299f5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ]. It=E2=80=99s a great way to sample the Write of Passage experienc=
e, prior to committing.
(1) America Is Back in the Factory Business [ https://link.sbstck.com/redir=
ect/459fc382-1858-43e4-9a87-358172821acb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
John Keilman [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/a29e5960-03e5-49a8-83bd-2f1=
ef6add7d3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] for The Wall Street Journal
Construction spending related to manufacturing reached $108 billion in 2022=
, Census Bureau data show, the highest annual total on record=E2=80=94more =
than was spent to build schools, healthcare centers or office buildings.
The Journal published an essay detailing just how =E2=80=9Cback=E2=80=9D ma=
nufacturing is in the U.S. The findings? Very back! But after decades of ou=
tsourcing manufacturing, the U.S. can=E2=80=99t suddenly decide to start ma=
ke everything again overnight. No, in order to manufacture more goods, the =
U.S. first needs to build more factories.
Construction spending related to manufacturing in 2022 reached $108B, the h=
ighest annual total in over 30 years. And with that surge of construction s=
pending, manufacturing capacity is expected to rise significantly in the ne=
xt couple of years (although it hasn=E2=80=99t moved the needle much yet.)
So why the big push for U.S. manufacturing?
On the public side, The Biden Administration has declared the production of=
 electric vehicles, semiconductors, and other goods a matter of national se=
curity. And the Administration has pumped tens of billions into onshoring t=
he capacity and talent needed to build those goods in the U.S.
On the private side, companies learned during the early days of the pandemi=
c that their fragile supply chains were a bit over reliant on China and cou=
ld benefit from producing some goods closet to home. Take Vireo Systems Inc=
, the makers of the popular creatine-based product CON-CR=C4=92T. Prior to =
covid, they imported all of their creatine from China, but experienced a ma=
jor shortage during 2021 due to the combination of a surge creatine popular=
ity and a totally backlogged shipping lanes from China to the U.S. For a pe=
riod of time, you basically couldn=E2=80=99t find creatine in the U.S. (whi=
ch is partially what prompted me to look into starting a creatine business.=
) Now, in a move that would=E2=80=99ve been unthinkable just a couple of ye=
ars ago, Vireo is opening up a creatine plant in Nebraska in order to have =
a more control over their supply.
With all this capacity coming on-line in the next couple of years, there ar=
e concerns over whether or not we=E2=80=99ll have the labor (both skilled a=
nd unskilled) to fill factories. On the unskilled side of things, the answe=
r (and hope) is that automation will largely fill the labor gaps and also k=
eep the costs of producing in the U.S. down. On the skilled side of things,=
 we have some work to do. A semiconductor plant in Arizona isn=E2=80=99t go=
ing to do much for us if we don=E2=80=99t have the labor to fill those high=
ly specialized jobs. One answer is importing that talent (which is likely w=
hat will happen for semiconductors specifically) and the other answer is a =
massive re-training of the American workers to re-establish the U.S. as a m=
anufacturing hub once again, we=E2=80=99ll likely need a lot of both.
(2) Chandrayaan-3 spacecraft lands on the moon in 'victory cry of a new Ind=
ia' [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/579ec6ce-5ade-4d45-994b-b22e8353fa00=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Nivedita Bhattacharjee [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/37bd3166-e560-4f9=
a-81db-ccf6937b937e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ] for Reuters
An Indian spacecraft became the first to land on the rugged, unexplored sou=
th pole of the moon [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/e7dfb587-42b3-4579-8=
aee-970a8d16ca87?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ] on Wednesday in a mission seen as crucial to lunar exploration a=
nd India's standing as a space power, just days after a similar Russian lan=
der crashed [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/2802c328-17c8-4077-a64a-ed3f=
e0dfa28d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ].
In what Prime Minister Narendra Modi called =E2=80=9Ca victory cry of a new=
 India,=E2=80=9D an Indian spacecraft landed on the south-side of the moon.=
 Chandrayaan-3=E2=80=99s landing makes India the fourth nation to successfu=
lly land on the moon, joining the U.S., China, and Russia. And they did it =
for only $75 million!=20
The landing is also particularly sweet, as it came just days after a Russia=
n craft crashed attempting to perform a similar landing. (Rumors out of Rus=
sia are that Putin thought Prigozhin was on the spacecraft.)=20
The location of landing on the south side of the moon also holds some scien=
tific importance, as its tough terrain could supply fuel, oxygen and drinki=
ng water for future missions.
But really, this is a matter of national pride for India. Nearly 7 Million =
people livestreamed the landing on Youtube. People across the country were =
glued to their televisions and then erupted into the streets to dance and c=
elebrate the landing. This was a one a one small step for man, one giant le=
ap for India type of moment. Earth=E2=80=99s most populace nation now has a=
 presence on the moon.
Chalo!
(3) Lux LP Letter Q2-2023 [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/904a2e6d-ff52-=
4b4b-a142-2b8972627ba0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Lux Capital [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/3108be05-fc1c-4d77-902a=
-11caabd0cce1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]
An hour of work today affords far more than any other time in the past, and=
 that is because human ingenuity created innovations that increased product=
ivity, which allowed us all to consume more for less and free up time gener=
ate even more new ideas. This is an arc of progress: we drift ever upwards.
Our friends over at Lux Capital released their most recent quarterly LP Let=
ter to the public this week. Lux is a venture capital firm that has for yea=
rs invested in cutting-edge science and hard-tech businesses; they help =E2=
=80=9Cturn sci-fi into sci-fact.=E2=80=9D
The letter focuses on the collapse of Time-Price over the course of recent =
history. To measure time-price, simply divide the nominal price by nominal =
hourly income, and the answer is how long you have to work to buy something=
=2E It=E2=80=99s a funny concept to think=20=
about, especially during periods of=
 high inflation. But the time-price of most anything today is lower than wh=
at it was 40 years ago. Back in 1980, a piece of gum may have cost $0.05, b=
ut you also had to work much longer to make that $0.05.
In Lux=E2=80=99s view, as Time-Price plummets, the arc of progress drifts u=
pwards.
Technology drives down time-price, which allows us to consume more for less=
, and to spend more time focusing on new ideas and new technologies. And th=
e cycle repeats and flywheels, forming the smooth, upwards sloping arc of p=
rogress we=E2=80=99ve experienced over the last couple of centuries.
This is a decidedly optimistic message coming from one of the firms most ag=
gressively investing in the technologies that cause some of us to be fearfu=
l of the future: AI, robotics, biotech. Their message is one of abundance. =
We need more people, more ideas, more technology all working towards drivin=
g down Time-Price.=20
(4) Dietary creatine and cancer risk in the U.S. population: NHANES 2017=E2=
=80=932020 [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/124a1b2a-5658-4e96-82f2-ad490=
6756401?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
]
Ostojic, Grasaas, Cvejic for Journal of Functional Foods
Consuming a diet that includes more creatine has been found to be associate=
d with a reduced risk of cancer or malignancy in U.S. adults aged 20=C2=A0y=
ears and over. In fact, for every additional milligram of food creatine per=
 kilogram of body mass consumed daily, the cancer rate is reduced by approx=
imately one percent.
It=E2=80=99s funny how life works. If you had told me just 3 years ago that=
 I=E2=80=99d be hawkishly following the latest in =E2=80=9Ccreatine researc=
h=E2=80=9D I wouldn=E2=80=99t have believed you. But alas. Staying up-to-da=
te on the latest in creatine research is how I spend much of my time these =
days. Which surprisingly, is more exciting than it sounds =E2=80=94 mostly =
because there=E2=80=99s been a rush of new creatine research over the last =
couple of years. Like this report from the Journal of Functional Foods, exa=
mining the relationship between dietary creatine intake and cancer risks. T=
he report, which was published this month, has two major findings:
Diet rich in creatine is associated with a reduced risk of cancer or malign=
ancy in U.S. adults aged 20=C2=A0years and over.
For every additional mg of creatine per kilogram of body mass consumed dail=
y, the cancer rate is reduced by =E2=88=BC one percent.
Now, the analysis isn=E2=80=99t perfect =E2=80=94 there are confounding var=
iables, it wasn=E2=80=99t a DBRCT, etc =E2=80=94 but the findings were pret=
ty clear: maintaining a creatine-rich diet reduces the risk of cancer. So w=
hat=E2=80=99s a creatine rich diet? Steak, beef, chicken, herring, salmon, =
tuna, and some dairy products. The study did not determine if exogenous cre=
atine supplementation also reduced the risk of cancer. More research is cer=
tainly needed, and when it comes, this creatine-loving newsletter writer wi=
ll be the first to share it with you.
(5) Scientists Say New Device Can Scrub 99.9% of Microplastics from Water [=
 https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/d0820fc1-dd28-499e-93b4-87834ca4b91b?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Noor Al-Sibai [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/b4798361-5ce6-4d6c-ad85-2c=
cb86fb2394?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for Futurism=20
Using fruit tannins coated over sawdust, the researchers were able to creat=
e a cylindrical water filtration device that eliminates between 95.2 and 99=
=2E9 percent of microplastics depending on what they're made of.
Packy here again. I love this kind of story.=20
Microplastics are a boogeyman that I=E2=80=99ve been vaguely aware of but l=
argely ignored because what=E2=80=99re ya gonna do? They live in the corner=
s of my brain somewhere between seed oils and 5G cancer. But some people ge=
t very worked up about microplastics. They=E2=80=99re one of the latest tre=
ndy terrors that will kill us all.=20
Well, not if scientists at Canada's University of British Columbia and Chin=
a's Sichuan University have anything to say about it! They figured out a wa=
y to use fruit and sawdust to filter between 95.2 and 99.9 of microplastics=
 out of water.=20
We need the Brita of microplastics filtration to scale the technology befor=
e we can officially pronounce this existential threat an ex-risk, but it lo=
oks like microplastics are on their way to join overpopulation and resource=
 depletion on the shelf of would-be killers tamed by a little human ingenui=
ty.=20
Humans rock.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

